               <interp inst="t18430130-778" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18430130"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18430130-778" type="date" value="18430130"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18430130-778-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-778-18430130 t18430130-778-offence-1 t18430130-778-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18430130-778-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-778-18430130 t18430130-778-offence-2 t18430130-778-verdict-2"></join>
               <p>778. <persName id="def1-778-18430130" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-778-18430130" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-778-18430130" type="age" value="40"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-778-18430130" type="surname" value="WHITEHEAD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-778-18430130" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">THOMAS WHITEHEAD</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted for<rs id="t18430130-778-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430130-778-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430130-778-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>stealing, on the <rs id="t18430130-cd-186" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430130-778-offence-1 t18430130-cd-186"></join>18th of Jan</rs>., 2 trusses of hay, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18430130-name-1155" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1155" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1155" type="surname" value="MILLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1155" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430130-778-offence-1 t18430130-name-1155"></join>John Miller</persName>, his master; and</rs>
                  <persName id="def2-778-18430130" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-778-18430130" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-778-18430130" type="age" value="41"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-778-18430130" type="surname" value="SPICER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-778-18430130" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">BENJAMIN SPICER</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18430130-778-offence-2" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430130-778-offence-2" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430130-778-offence-2" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp>, for feloniously receiving the same, well knowing it to have been stolen; against the Statute, &amp;c.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1157" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1157" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1157" type="surname" value="PARSFIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1157" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN PARSFIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Church-street, Lisson-grove, next door to Mr. Miller, who deals in corn and hay—Whitehead has been in his employ for the last month—on Wednesday evening, the 18th of Jan., I saw him take a truss of clover hay out of Mr. Miller's barn, and put it down against Spicer's door, who lives in Duke-mews, next door but one to Miller's stable—Spicer was standing at his door at the time—I made my way towards them—they appeared to be in conversation—I said to Whitehead, "<hi rend="italic">Tom</hi>, I think I shall go and get a pint of beer"—Whitehead then made his way from Spicer's, and I could neither see the clover, nor Spicer—I did not go to get any beer, but went and stood at the corner—I then saw Whitehead come again out of the barn with a truss of bent hay on his shoulder, which he took to Spicer's door—I then saw Spicer bring the truss of bent hay from the door up into Earl-street—I saw Spicer's man with the truss of clover hay on his back—I went to Mr. Miller's shopman, and told him what I had seen.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you see Spicer at the door? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I do not know where he was then—I was standing at the corner of Duke's-mews, and in about five or six minutes I saw Spicer with the bent hay on his back—he came from the door with it—I did not see him take it from the door—I did riot see him take it up—I had seen Spicer's man with a truss before that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How near was Spicer to his own door? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About five or six yards off.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1158" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1158" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1158" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1158" type="given" value="THOMAS HENRY"></interp>THOMAS HENRY THOMPSON</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant D</hi> 4.) On Saturday night, the 21st of Jan., I went to Mr. Miller's counting-house, in consequence of information—Whitehead came into the counting-house while I was there—I said I was going to take him into custody—he asked what for—I said, "For stealing a truss of clover, and a truss of bent hay"—he said, "Why you asto<lb></lb>nish me"—he asked when—I said, "On Wednesday night"—he then said, "I know nothing about it"—I said he need not say any thing, I had a witness who saw him take two trusses from his master's to Spicer's door—he then said, "I will tell you the truth; I did take them to Spicer's, and Spicer re<lb></lb>ceived them"—on the road to the station, he said Spicer had been round to him that evening, and asked if he could have four or five more trusses, and he (Whitehead) told him he could not let him have them, but Spicer was in the habit of having a good deal of loose hay—I took him to the station, and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184301300193"></xptr>
               <p>he returned to No. 2, Duke's-mews, where Spicer lives—I went up stairs, and found him in bed—I told him to get up, Mr. Miller wanted him—he asked his wife if she had paid for the oats and chaff that night—I said it was not about the oats and chaff that I took him, but on suspicion of receiving a truss of clover, and a truss of bent hay—he said he had bad no hay, and did not know Mr. Miller's man—I said a wit<lb></lb>ness saw him, and saw the hay come to his door, that Whitehead said he had taken the hay to him, and he had received it—he said he did not, he never had any hay of him—I said Whitehead had told me that he had been round that evening to know if he would let him have four or five more trusses—he said he had not been to Whitehead, and had not seen him—I took him to the station, and the two prisoners were there together—the inspector asked him, and Spicer said he knew nothing about it—Whitehead said something which I did not hear—Spicer then said, "Is that them? I will pay Mr. Miller for them if he will go next door, the money lies there"—I was present when the depo<lb></lb>sitions were taken—that is Mr. Rawlinson's signature to this deposition—they were all signed in my presence—(<hi rend="italic">read</hi>)—"The prisoner Spicer says, 'I sever received them, and have not had a truss of hay in my place for three weeks.' <hi rend="smallCaps">J. RAWLINSON</hi>."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1159" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1159" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1159" type="surname" value="MILLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1159" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN MILLER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a corn-dealer, and live in Lisson-grove North. Whitehead was a chaff-cutter, and helper in my service—he had no authority to take any clover hay, or bent hay, without my order, or that of my shop<lb></lb>man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Is this where your business is carried on? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, in this stable, at the back of my house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1160" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1160" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1160" type="surname" value="WARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1160" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES WARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to the prosecutor. I did not authorise Whitehead to take these trusses of hay.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Whitehead's Defence.</hi> The keys of the warehouse are left with me ill day, and when the carters come at any time I serve then; sometimes I get an order, and sometimes not.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">WHITEHEAD</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18430130-778-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
